Rating: 0
Loved, loved, loved this recipe. These were very light on filler and heavy on seafood. I followed another reviewer's advice and used 1 lb. of scallops and 1 lb. of shrimp. I also only processed 1/4 of the mixture of seafood, and added the rest of the chopped seafood to that mix after processing, which worked really well. It held together wonderfully while cooking. I make these for a cocktail party so made them bite-sized, cooked them ahead of time, 2 minutes a side, and kept them warm in a 200 degree oven--worked great. I made the red onion marmalade, but did not feel that it complemented the flavors of the seafood all that well. I used instead a cajun style remoulade sauce (online) instead. My guests raved about it.

Rating: 4
I thought these were fabulous. I live on the coast so we eat a lot of seafood, and these are definitely going into permanent rotation. I made them almost exactly as the recipe directs, with a couple of changes: I don't like panko, so I used coarsely crumbled Ritz and oyster crackers instead, but in the same amounts as the recipe states for panko. Also, I made them about half the size that the recipe suggests, I ended up with 11 rather than 6. That was the perfect size in my opinion, the proportion of soft inside to crunchy outside was ideal. This exceeded my (high) expectations by quite a lot. I loved the sauce, but the kids wouldn't eat it- too sharp for their tastes. I want to make this next week for a guest who dislikes cilantro. I'm not sure which way I'll go with it, possibly some curry flavor in the cakes and a coconut milk-based sauce.

Rating: 4
I have made this two ways now- once with cilantro and once without. Both times I was very pleased with the outcome. The second time I took the below reviewers' advice and made the Red Onion Marmalade. Delicious! It complimented the cakes very well, I cant wait to use it again with this dish and others! The cakes taste great and are easy to make. Highly recommended.

